stanzas.stanza_text:
Paint Scotland greetan owre her thrissle;
Her mutchkin stowp as toom's a whissle;
An' d — mn'd Excise-men in a bussle,
Seizan a Stell,
Triumphant crushan't like a muscle
Or laimpet shell.

Dempster, a true-blue Scot I'se warran;
Thee, aith-detesting, chalk Kilkerran;
An' that glib-gabbet Highland Baron,
The Laird o' Graham;
And ane, a chap that's d — mn'd auldfarran,
Dundas his name.

Erskine, a spunkie norland billie;
True Campbells, Frederick an' Ilay;
An' Livistone, the bauld Sir Willie;
An' monie ithers,
Whom auld Demosthenes or Tully
Might own for brithers.

Auld Scotland has a raucle tongue;
She's just a devil wi' a rung;
An' if she promise auld or young
To tak their part,
Tho' by the neck she should be strung,
She'll no desert.

Their gun's a burden on their shouther;
They downa bide the stink o' powther;
Their bauldest thought's a hank'ring swither,
To stan' or rin,
Till skelp — a shot — they're aff, a' throw'ther,
To fave their skin.

Nae cauld, faint-hearted doubtings tease him;
Death comes, wi' fearless eye he sees him;
Wi' bluidy han' a welcome gies him;
An' when he fa's,
His latest draught o' breathin lea'es him
In faint huzzas.
